english:
  title: A Treatise on Compassionate Justice and Criminal Law
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Punishment is an instrument that aids in governance. Even in the most prosperous eras of antiquity, it cannot be abandoned. When the sage-king Shun ruled as Son of Heaven, he was concerned solely with ensuring that punishments were just. When Gao Yao served as judge, he clarified the five categories of punishment and upheld the five teachings, thereby achieving harmonious governance. How glorious that was indeed! Yet when the Qin Dynasty's First Emperor came to power, he exalted only cruelty and tyranny. Zhao Gao and his cohort pursued harshness and haste, stripping law of all mercy and compassion, until the dynasty collapsed within two generations. Should we not learn from this?

    The prison determines matters of life and death. If we fail to discover the true circumstances and resort to beating confessions from suspects, the guilty may escape through good fortune while the innocent fall into snares. When punishment fails to find its proper mark, people harbor resentment and bear injustice, never finding redress. This wounds the harmony of heaven and earth, summoning droughts and floods. This affliction spans all ages. I grieve deeply over this and have studied the chronicles of criminal justice through the dynasties. Let me recount the most striking cases.

    During the Jin Dynasty, in Linzi County, there lived a widow who faithfully served her mother-in-law. The mother-in-law, seeing her young age, urged her to remarry. The widow refused to abandon her vow. The mother-in-law, moved by this devotion, took her own life in secret. Her relatives accused the widow of murder. Officials interrogated her, and under severe torture, the widow confessed falsely to escape further agony. Her doom seemed certain. Fortunately, Cao Shu became county magistrate. Recognizing her innocence, he reopened the case and uncovered the truth. The world praised his wisdom.

    During the Tang Dynasty, when the rebel Wu Yuanji rose in Huaixi, the Emperor entrusted all military affairs to Prime Minister Wu Yuanheng to suppress him. Wang Chengzong of Chengde sent an emissary to the Department of State Affairs to advocate for Wu Yuanji, but his words were disrespectful. Yuanheng rebuked and dismissed him. Chengzong later submitted a memorial attacking Yuanheng. When Yuanheng died, Wang Shize reported that Chengzong had sent assassin Zhang Yan to kill him. The suspects were arrested and confessed. They were executed. Later, when Li Shidao of Pinglu was subdued, his documents were examined. Among them was found a record of a reward offered for killing Yuanheng. Only then did they discover that the true assassin was not Chengzong but Li Shidao.

    During the Song Dynasty, Qian Ruoshui served as investigating magistrate of Tongzhou. A wealthy family's young maidservant had fled. The maid's parents sued before the prefecture. The recording clerk was assigned to investigate. This clerk had once sought to borrow money from the wealthy family and been refused. In revenge, he charged the family with murdering the maid and disposing of her body in the river, claiming the body could not be recovered. Under brutal beating, the family confessed. The prefect's review found no objection to their guilt. Only Qian Ruoshui harbored doubt. He held the case in suspension for days, refusing to seal it. The clerk berated him: "Have you been bribed by the wealthy family to release them from capital punishment?" Ruoshui smiled and replied, "Several people face death here. Should I not linger a few more days to examine their words carefully?" He delayed ten days more. The prefect repeatedly pressed for resolution, to no avail. All grew puzzled. One morning, Ruoshui met privately with the prefect and said, "The reason I have kept this case open is that I secretly sent people to search for the maidservant. I have now found her." He then secretly had the maid brought to the prefect's residence. The prefect lowered the screen and questioned the parents: "Do you recognize your daughter?" They replied, "How could we not?" The maid was presented to them from behind the screen. The parents wept and said, "It is indeed our daughter." The family was completely exonerated. The daughter's parents wept with gratitude: "Without Your Excellency, our entire family would have perished." The prefect replied, "This is the achievement of the investigating magistrate." When Emperor Taizong heard this, he rapidly promoted Ruoshui.

    There was also a household in Hubei consisting of only a husband and wife. The wife, being beautiful, was discontent with her husband. A fortune-teller happened to lodge there. The wife, attracted to his refined appearance, murdered her husband and revealed the deed, proposing they flee together. The fortune-teller, outraged by her depravity, pretended to comply. He took her husband's dagger, killed her with it, and departed. At dawn, a regular laborer who worked at the house discovered two corpses lying together in a pool of blood. Fearing involvement, he fled. Soon neighbors discovered the scene and arrested the laborer. He could not defend himself and confessed falsely. The fortune-teller continued his trade in the market undisturbed. When he heard the laborer faced execution, he turned himself in and revealed the truth. The authorities considered the fortune-teller's killing of the unfaithful wife as balancing her murder of her husband. Since he had also confessed voluntarily, he was deemed virtuous and released along with the laborer.

    There was also one Wang Sanlang who lived in a tower overlooking a river in Linjiang. His wife, leaning on the railing while eating fruit, accidentally dropped a seed that fell onto a young man's head in a boat below. The man looked up, and thinking the woman was signaling to him, went to the house at dusk. Finding it silent and empty, he returned to his boat. He noticed his shoes had become damp and hung them by the fire to dry. That night, Wang Sanlang returned home to find his wife murdered, the ground awash with blood. The next morning, neighbors investigating found bloody footprints leading directly to the boat, so they arrested the young man. He could not defend himself and confessed falsely. Only the woman's shoes and the murder weapon were missing. An interrogator pointed to a wooden marker near the river pavilion, suggesting something lay there. Indeed, the shoes and knife were found. The case seemed settled. However, Chen Qing, an interrogation officer, harbored suspicion. He obtained leave to return home. Walking along the river at dawn, he met Wang's neighbor woman, who asked about the case. Chen replied, "We are executing the boatman." The woman gasped: "The true culprit is one of the jailers!" Chen immediately reported this to the investigating magistrate. Under interrogation, the jailer confessed. The young man was freed, and the jailer was executed.

    During the Yuan Dynasty, in Pingxiang of Yuan Prefecture, there was a high ridge. North of the ridge lived someone surnamed Zhang who had married a woman surnamed Zhou from south of the ridge. When his wife returned from visiting her family, Zhang sent his younger brother to meet her. Crossing the ridge, the wife grew tired and rested. The brother carried their child ahead and returned home. His wife did not follow. When she failed to appear, Zhang and his brother went to where she had rested but found nothing. They went to the Zhou household—she was not there either. Searching the ridge again with the Zhous, they discovered her corpse in thick brush, beheaded. The Zhous took Zhang's brother to the authorities, suspecting he had murdered her and beheaded her to silence her. The brother confessed falsely. Officials demanded the head and dagger from the coroner. The coroner provided them. The brother was condemned to death. Over a year later, two of Zhang's neighbors encountered Zhang's wife in an inn in Jiankang. They stared in amazement. The neighbors learned her story: while resting on the ridge, a bearded man carrying a shouldering pole had come up the mountain. Seeing no one around, he drew his dagger and threatened her, stealing her clothes and shoes. He had a woman in the pole—he dressed her in the stolen garments, severed her head, placed it in the pole, threw the body into the brush, forced his wife into the pole, and carried her away. After more than half a month they arrived here. Soon after, the bearded man appeared. The neighbors arrested him and reported to the authorities. He submitted to confession without resistance. The authorities received imperial sanction to execute him. His victim's brother's death was balanced by his own. The coroner and county officials faced tattoos and confiscation. The county magistrate and investigating magistrate were demoted and dismissed. The coroner, under pressure from officials, had stolen the head from another coffin to present as evidence. He too was executed.

    There was a woodworker in Beijing's lumber bureau who had quarreled with his foreman over some matter and could not yield. The worker severed relations with him. Seeing their dispute as trivial, other workers raised money for wine and meat and forcibly brought the two together for reconciliation. After they parted in evening drunkenness, the worker's wife, who was unfaithful, had long plotted with her lover to kill her husband but lacked opportunity. This drunken night, with her husband intoxicated from resentment against his rival, presented the chance. They killed him hastily and, unable to hide the body elsewhere, removed the floor tiles of the room, placed the corpse in the space below, and covered it as before. The next day the wife went to the foreman's house and wept: "My husband did not return yesterday. You must have killed him." She sued before the Police Bureau. The Bureau, knowing the foreman was his rival, arrested him and beat him. Unable to endure the torture, the foreman confessed falsely. The Bureau asked where the body lay. He said it was thrown into a ditch. They blamed two coroners to search the ditch without success. The Ministry of Punishment, Censorate, and Capital officials all pressed urgently for the case's completion, setting deadlines of ten days, seven days, five days, three days. Even after four beatings, they could not find the body, and the deadline drew ever closer. In desperation, the two coroners conspired to murder an innocent and produce the corpse. At evening they sat by water. An old man on a donkey crossed a bridge. They pushed him into the water and set the donkey free. Fearing the appearance would not match, they dared not present it immediately. After more beatings over many days, they reckoned the body sufficiently decomposed to be unrecognizable. They reported it to the Bureau. The Bureau summoned the wife to examine it. She embraced the corpse and wailed: "It is he!" She took his clothing and called his spirit by the water. She removed her hairpins and earrings, prepared a coffin, and gave him burial. The case was sealed. The Bureau sent the foreman's execution order to higher authority, but approval had not been granted. The donkey owner's family searched everywhere for their kinsman without success. One man appeared carrying the donkey's skin on the road. They arrested him and sued to the county, which also subjected him to cruel interrogation. Unable to bear it, he confessed to robbing and murdering the man, claiming the body lay at a certain location. When they went seeking it, they found nothing. He then named another location. His confessions kept changing, yet the body was never found. The man bearing the donkey skin wasted away and died in prison. Over a year later, the foreman's execution was approved. The other workers, outraged at his injustice yet unable to clear his name, collected a hundred stringed coins and posted notices throughout the city, offering the reward to anyone who could discover the woodworker's true fate. One day, a thief planning to burgle a house found it too early. In the darkness, he waited by the wall of the woodworker's wife's house. As the hour approached, a drunken man stumbled in, grew angry and vile-mouthed, cursed the woman, struck her with fists and feet. She dared not cry out. After the drunk fell asleep, the woman muttered softly by candlelight: "Because of you, I killed my husband. His remains lie buried under the floor for more than two years. I cannot burn the house, nor dare I properly dispose of them. I do not even know if my husband has completely decomposed. And now you abuse me." She sighed and wept. The thief outside the window heard everything and silently rejoiced: "Why commit theft?" At daybreak he rushed into the lumber bureau and shouted to all the workers: "I have discovered the woodworker's true fate! Quickly give me the reward!" He had them follow him to the wife's house. He removed the floor tiles and the corpse was revealed. The workers burst in and forcibly took the woman to the authorities. She confessed completely. The drunken man was her paramour. The authorities then investigated whose corpse lay in the ditch. The coroner confessed to pushing a donkey-riding man into the water. The coroner was executed. The wife and her lover were torn asunder in the marketplace. The officials who had urged the foreman's death were imprisoned for life. Though the authorities learned the water's corpse was the man who had died in prison, revealing this would mean condemning several more officials. Thus they suppressed the truth. The man bearing the donkey skin's innocence was never established. The woodworker should only have been avenged by his wife and paramour, yet through these entanglements, four or five people lost their lives. This is how events become so confused that truth becomes impossible to discern. Reading history to this point, I am deeply moved.

    Considering our own realm's recent cases: In the year Imsin, the servant woman Yuanjang of this palace and her son Gaeyomi accused Seongun Imseongbu of speaking improperly at our home. The Seoncheon magistrate immediately arrested Seongbu and beat him in interrogation three times before obtaining a confession. The Saheonbu reviewed the case with two beatings but still could not establish the facts. Moreover, when Gaeyomi spoke with the fortune-teller Bokryong, what he reported matched what was told to the Seoncheon official. Yet when speaking with Boksan, he never mentioned that Seongbu said such things. These contradictions were never clarified to make the accounts consistent. Instead, officials assumed Seongbu had indeed spoken such words but refused to confess, and they ceased further investigation. Thus they wrongly condemned Seongbu to death. I had the six ministries convene to deliberate—all agreed he deserved death. Yet I harbored doubts and transferred the case to the Forbidden Guard Office for further questioning of Seongbu about the origin of his alleged words. Then Yuanjang confessed that she held a grudge against Seongbu and schemed to frame him, desiring only to see him beaten. Seongbu had never spoken such words. Thus Seongbu was freed, and Yuanjang faced punishment instead. Had we not reopened the case to discover the truth, Seongbu's execution would have been certain.

    In the year Giyou, bandits ambushed and killed the Japanese interpreter Yi Chunbal on a night road, leaving his staff. Chunbal's son-in-law reported: "A female shaman Juyeon and her son Saja, who harbored long resentment toward my father-in-law, are suspects. My father-in-law died near Saja's house. When we servants knocked on Saja's door calling out, he refused to come out. The circumstances are very suspicious." The Forbidden Guard Office arrested and interrogated them. Saja's younger brother, Sangyi, testified: "My brother, with the neighbor Kim Sokkummi and Kim Maeumdong, had accumulated resentment against Chunbal and often planned to strike him dead. This time we combined our efforts." The interrogator also brought Saja's staff to the house. A wooden plank was missing from Saja's fence—when they inserted the staff into the vacant hole, it fit perfectly and matched in length. The interrogator subjected Juyeon, Saja, Sokkummi, and Maeumdong to severe torture including knee-breaking, yet they would not confess. However, Sangyi's account was uncontradicted, and with the staff as evidence, the case appeared nearly complete. I then offered substantial rewards for information about who killed Chunbal. The Border Minister reported that Hongseongbu and Kim Saenggeon harbored old grievances against Chunbal and were likely the culprits. I immediately arrested both and rigorously interrogated them. Both confessed. When questioned about his accomplices, Saenggeon concealed the true perpetrators and falsely implicated the Japanese slave Bossu and the slave Ganch'ung. Unable to bear torture, both confessed to acting with Saenggeon to commit the murder. Moreover, Ganch'ung's confession was especially detailed—he described the location where they watched, the manner of attack, how Chunbal's head and feet struck the ground with exceptional precision. The interrogator brought them to the death scene for verification and it matched perfectly. Later, when they arrested the actual perpetrator Iduk and interrogated him, they learned that Bossu had never participated in the plot and was freed along with Saja's group. Ganch'ung, it turned out, had no knowledge of the facts but merely heard Saenggeon's words and called Chunbal onto the road—he did not participate in the killing and received a reduced sentence. Hongseongbu and his two accomplices were sentenced to death. Had the Border Minister not reported this, Saja and the others would have faced the most severe punishment. Is this not a grave injustice?

    The officials' storehouse of Yongheung prefecture was robbed. Someone submitted an anonymous denunciation accusing the official slaves Yeonman, Gasatdong, and Naeeundal. The prefect believed it and arrested them, detained them, and interrogated them under torture, but could not establish facts and released them. Soon after, the military arsenal caught fire. The provincial governor ordered investigation of who set the fire, but the culprit could not be determined. When Yeonman and Naeeundal had fled, the prefect suspected them of arson and arrested Gasatdong, subjecting him to cruel torture. Gasatdong could not endure and confessed falsely that he and Yeonman and Naeeundal had conspired to commit arson. The prefect then had government clerks re-interrogate him. The clerks' beating was even more severe. A provincial inspector's delegate also came to verify facts and also extracted forced confessions from all. When Yeonman and Naeeundal voluntarily turned themselves in to the prison seeking to clear themselves, the prefect interrogated them, the clerks interrogated them, and the delegate interrogated them again. All employed excessive torture to secure confessions matching what Gasatdong had said. Naeeundal endured hundreds of beatings and died. The provincial governor sent another delegate to continue investigation. Yeonman and Gasatdong, hoping to escape this time, desperately insisted there had been no arson, but the officials refused to reverse their verdicts. Beatings intensified. Then came knee-breaking torture three times, and forced confessions were constructed. The provincial governor, Ministry of Justice, and State Council reviewed the case in sequence but did not submit it to the throne. It proceeded to capital punishment. I, finding the case's origins lacking clear evidence and the facts difficult to establish, suspended judgment with hesitation. I sent investigating officials to examine it and transferred the case to the Forbidden Guard Office for thorough investigation. They discovered no evidence the crime had occurred. I then condemned the officials from the Ministry of Justice downward, and immediately freed Gasatdong, Yeonman, and others. Examining the case record, Gasatdong had received over thirteen hundred beatings and Yeonman nearly four hundred. Under the merciless rod, who cannot confess anything desired? This is what the ancients meant.

    This past summer, a Buddhist monk dwelling in a grass hut outside the Water Gate was slain by armed bandits. The surviving monk Haejon reported it to authorities as the work of stonemasons in the village. The Forbidden Guard Office arrested and interrogated them. A slave named Maksan belonging to Kimgyeong testified: "On the ninth of the fourth month at night, together with Seojung, Bakyon, Duji, Bujohn, and Igagi, I went to the north of the grass hut at Baleophyeun outside the Water Gate to watch. Near the second watch of night, Bujohn struck flints and ignited dry grass. When we reached the hut, seeing a monk coming out to relieve himself, Bakyon struck him with a small staff and he fell as if dead. Bujohn threw the burning straw into the dharma hall. Another monk came out and threw the straw back outside. Bujohn then tore the roof grass, ignited it, placed it in the dharma hall, threw stones randomly, and threatened the monks saying, 'If you do not give us all your stored wealth, I will kill every one of you.' The monks then called out in distress and gave us everything. Then two monks escaped and we chased and caught one near Ganch'eon. Bakyon struck him with the staff and he fell again. Bakyon and the others pelted his head and face with stones. We caught another monk below the food distribution platform and many of us tied him and beat him wildly. Then we withdrew into the fields and lay scattered until dawn when we entered the city." Maksan also testified that the stolen goods were buried beside the chopping stone at the master's house, and that the master's wife Sogeun and Igagi's wife Changsae knew of this. When Changsae was beaten and interrogated, she testified: "On the tenth, Igagi wrapped the stolen goods in cloth and hid them in the empty space under the forge board. I asked what it was and Igagi said it was none of my concern and told me to keep quiet. That evening after dinner, Igagi took the stolen goods out again." Changsae later recanted: "What I said about the tenth was wrong. In fact, it was the eleventh, after the interrogators searched the master's house. I then took the goods Igagi had hidden and burned them in the kitchen." Twelve stonemasons from near the hut were arrested and lined up in the courtyard. Haejon was asked to identify the bandits. He pointed to Bujohn, Bakyon, Seojung, and Duji, all slaves of Kimgyeong, saying, "These are the bandits I saw." The next day, twenty others were lined up and Bujohn and the others were made to change clothes and mingle among them. Haejon again identified four and specifically pointed to Bakyon, saying, "This man beat most harshly." Bakyon's complexion changed and his fear appeared different from the others. Haejon also reported: "When the bandits bound me, I happened to grab a stone and struck a bandit's foot, so he should have a wound. Also, after they left, I found a hemp-rope sandal they had discarded." The interrogator examined many people and found Bujohn indeed had a wound on his foot. Asked about the sandal's owner, all said it was Bujohn's regular wear. The interrogator had no further doubts and the case seemed nearly complete. On the nineteenth of the fourth month, the actual bandits Bakmwan and Mangooji were captured at Yeonseoyuk. Interrogated at the Forbidden Guard Office, they fully confessed the truth. The gang was large and genuine stolen goods were recovered. Only then did officials realize that Maksan and the others had testified falsely, motivated only by fear of torture. Maksan and the rest were freed. But for the capture of Bakmwan and the others, Maksan and his group would have received severe punishment.

    From this we may observe that arriving at truth in criminal investigation is genuinely difficult. Reflecting on past events, how can we know whether such injustices have not already occurred? Every time I consider this, my heart grows cold. I observe that among officials who judge criminal cases in all regions, once the initial interrogation documents are prepared, subsequent reviewers nearly always merely embellish what exists, rarely examining facts carefully and seeking truth. The cases of Sangyi and Maksan occurred recently in the capital. The legal authorities and censorate met with investigating officials at the Forbidden Guard Office for questioning, yet even so fell into such errors. What then of distant provinces?

    Alas, the dead cannot be revived. The executed cannot have their heads restored. Should we but once fail in judgment, what avails regret? This is what troubles me day and night, never leaving my heart for a moment.

    From now forward, those of you appointed as law enforcement officials throughout my realm must take the past as mirror and the present as warning. Be meticulous and clear; maintain an open and receptive mind. Do not cling to personal views; do not favor preconceived conclusions. Do not simply follow established precedent; do not value speed in concluding cases. Inquire through many methods and investigate repeatedly, so that the dead harbor no resentment in the nine springs and the living carry no regret in their hearts. May all people be satisfied, prisons fall empty, and harmony spread widely to bring timely rain and abundant sunshine. Let the Ministry of Justice comprehend this profound intention and disseminate it throughout the realm.
  footnotes:
    - 'The Five Punishments (五刑): ancient forms of punishment including tattooing, nose removal, foot removal, castration, and capital punishment.'
    - 'The Five Teachings (五教): often interpreted as the five fundamental human relationships (ruler-subject, father-son, husband-wife, elder-younger, friend-friend).'
    - 'Zhao Gao: a Qin Dynasty official who advocated using cruel punishments to intimidate officials and magistrates.'
    - 'Coroners (仵作): officials responsible for examining injury marks and managing criminal investigations.'
